Load the libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(ggmap)
library(albersusa)

Load the Data

We will use two separate data sets for this homework.

  1. The first data set represent sightings of grizzly bears (Ursos arctos) in Alaska.

  2. The second data set is from Brandell, Ellen E (2021), Serological dataset and R code for: Patterns and processes of pathogen exposure in gray wolves across North America, Dryad, Dataset.

  3. Load the grizzly data and evaluate its structure. As part of this step, produce a summary that provides the range of latitude and longitude so you can build an appropriate bounding box.

grizzly <- read_csv(here("lab12", "data", "bear-sightings.csv")) %>% clean_names()

  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
lat <- c(55.02, 70.37)
long <- c(-166.2, -131.3)
bbox <- make_bbox(long, lat, f = 0.05)
  1. Load a map from stamen in a terrain style projection and display the map.
bearmap <- get_map(bbox, maptype = "terrain", source = "stamen")
## Map tiles by Stamen Design, under CC BY 3.0. Data by OpenStreetMap, under ODbL.
ggmap(bearmap)

  1. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of grizzly bears in Alaska.
ggmap(bearmap) + 
  geom_point(data = grizzly, aes(longitude, latitude)) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", title = "Grizzly Sightings")

  1. How many distinct wolf populations are included in this study? Make a new object that restricts the data to the wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
wolves %>% 
  summarize(n_populations=n_distinct(pop))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   n_populations
##           <int>
## 1            17
wolves48 <- wolves %>% 
  filter(lat <= 50, lat >= 27)
  1. Use the albersusa package to make a base map of the lower 48 US states.
us_composite <- usa_sf()
composite48 <- us_composite %>% 
  filter(name!="Alaska",name!="Hawaii")
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = composite48, size = 0.125) + 
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title = "Lower 48 US States")

  1. Use the relimited data to plot the distribution of wolf populations in the lower 48 US states.
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = composite48, size = 0.125) + 
  theme_linedraw()+
  labs(title = "Wolf Populations in the Lower 48 US States")+
  geom_point(data = wolves48, aes(long, lat))

  1. What is the average pack size for the wolves in this study by region?
packsize <- wolves %>% 
  group_by(pop, lat, long) %>% 
  summarize(mean_pack_size = mean(pack_size, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'pop', 'lat'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

  1. Make a new map that shows the distribution of wolves in the lower 48 US states but which has the size of location markers adjusted by pack size.
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = composite48, size = 0.25) + 
  theme_linedraw()+
  geom_point(data = wolves48, aes(long, lat, size=pack_size))+
   labs(title = "Wolf Populations in the Lower 48 US States",
       x="Longitude",y="Latitude")
